#### Bandwidth throttling

Virgin Media, with a straight face, consistently asserts on its consumer website that it does *not* engage in [throttling](/Bandwidth_throttling) users' download or upload bandwidth &#91;85&#93;. However, the reality, as often happens with corporate pronouncements, has proven somewhat more nuanced. In 2013, the company quietly updated its traffic management policy &#91;86&#93; &#91;87&#93;. This revised policy stipulated a maximum throttling amount of 40% on most services, yet numerous users reported experiencing far more aggressive slowdowns, with some claiming to be throttled by as much as 54% &#91;88&#93;. Unsurprisingly, Virgin Media's advertisements, particularly those touting "unlimited" broadband services in conjunction with its rather controversial traffic management practices, attracted the attention of the [Advertising Standards Authority](/Advertising_Standards_Authority_(United_Kingdom)), especially after previous advertisements had already faced bans &#91;89&#93;.

A notable shift occurred on 28 February 2014, when Virgin Media announced a significant policy change: it would be scrapping traffic management entirely for downstream traffic on packages offering 30 [Mbit/s](/Data-rate_units) or higher speeds. Consequently, these higher-tier packages would only experience throttling on the upstream, while packages of 20 Mbit/s or below remained subject to throttling on both upstream and downstream traffic &#91;90&#93;. Sometime after this, the company once again refined its policy, now unequivocally stating on its website that, regardless of the broadband package chosen, users would not be subjected to any bandwidth throttling whatsoever &#91;91&#93;. One can only hope this latest declaration truly sticks, for the sake of consumer trust and clarity.

### London Underground

In a significant infrastructure victory, Virgin Media secured an exclusive contract in March 2012 to provide [Wi-Fi](/Wi-Fi) access across [London Underground](/London_Underground) platforms, an agreement slated to run until 2017 &#91;92&#93;. The company quickly mobilized, announcing plans to equip 80 stations with mobile internet access by July 2012, with a further 40 stations targeted for completion by the end of that year &#91;93&#93;. This service offered access to mobile internet via a dedicated [Transport for London (TfL)](/Transport_for_London) portal, which provided a curated selection of travel information, news updates, and entertainment bulletins. Crucially, access to this service remained free for Virgin Media customers, as well as subscribers of partnered companies such as [Vodafone](/Vodafone_UK) and [EE](/EE_(telecommunications)), particularly after the conclusion of the [2012 Summer Olympics](/2012_Summer_Olympics). Other users, however, were granted only a limited amount of free content through the TfL portal, with full mobile internet services available on a more conventional pay-as-you-go basis. A smart move to leverage existing customer bases and attract new ones.

### Virgin Media Business

*   Main article: [Virgin Media Business](/Virgin_Media_Business)

On 11 February 2010, ntl:Telewest Business underwent a significant rebranding, emerging as [Virgin Media Business](/Virgin_Media_Business). This change marked the definitive end of the NTL and Telewest brand names being actively used by the company &#91;94&#93;. Under its new identity, Virgin Media Business focuses on delivering specialized internet and [telecommunications](/Telecommunication) services tailored specifically for the needs of corporate clients and enterprises. A pragmatic separation of consumer and business offerings, as one might expect.

### Virgin Phone

Virgin Phone operates as the company's dedicated provider of [landline telephone](/Landline) services within the UK. In this segment, it holds a respectable position as the number two service provider, trailing only the historically dominant [BT Group](/BT_Group), which, of course, was once the UK's state-owned monopoly &#91;95&#93;. In a notable move to enhance its offering and provide additional value to customers, Virgin Media introduced free home phone to mobile calls on 1 April 2010. This allowed Virgin Phone customers the convenience of calling Virgin Mobile customers at no additional charge, provided these calls fell within the stipulated periods of their chosen Talk Plan &#91;96&#93;. A clever way to create synergy between their fixed and mobile offerings.

### Virgin TV

*   Main article: [Virgin TV](/Virgin_TV)

[Virgin TV](/Virgin_TV), the company's digital [cable television](/Cable_television) service, has historically held a significant position in the UK's competitive pay-TV market. As of Q3 2007, it ranked as the second-largest pay TV provider, boasting 3.6 million subscribers, though still considerably behind BSkyB's dominant 8.2 million &#91;97&#93;. At that time, a substantial 55% of UK households had potential access to Virgin's extensive network &#91;98&#93;. Virgin TV particularly distinguished itself as the UK's leading provider of [on-demand content](/Video_on_Demand) (VoD). By October 2011, it had cultivated a base of over 3 million VoD customers, who could access an impressive library exceeding 6,500 hours of programming &#91;99&#93;. A clear early leader in what would become the pervasive streaming model.

## Former operations

### Virgin Mobile (1999–2023)

The former headquarters of Virgin Mobile in Trowbridge, Wiltshire.

*   Main article: [Virgin Mobile (UK)](/Virgin_Mobile_(UK))

For many years, Virgin Media operated Virgin Mobile Telecoms Limited, a prominent UK-based [Mobile Virtual Network Operator](/Mobile_Virtual_Network_Operator) (MVNO). This venture, which commenced in November 1999, initially utilized the [one2one](/T-Mobile_UK) network, which subsequently evolved into T-Mobile and later [EE](/EE_(telecommunications)). However, following the momentous merger between Virgin Media and [Telefónica](/Telef%C3%B3nica), a strategic decision was made: Virgin Mobile would cease operations, and its existing customer base would be seamlessly migrated to the [O2](/O2_(UK)) network. This comprehensive migration process was successfully completed by August 2023, and Virgin Mobile officially ceased all operations on 31 August 2023. A logical consolidation, if a little sad for brand loyalists, given the new ownership structure.

### Virgin Media Television

*   Main article: [Living TV Group](/Living_TV_Group)

Virgin Media Television (VMtv), which previously operated under the name Flextech, served as the content subsidiary of Virgin Media. This division was responsible for operating a portfolio of wholly owned channels, a lineup that included [Bravo](/Bravo_(UK)), [LIVING](/Living_(channel)), [Trouble](/Trouble_(TV)), and [Challenge](/Challenge_(TV_channel)). A notable expansion occurred on 1 October 2007, with the launch of [Virgin1](/Virgin1) on both [Freeview](/Freeview_(UK)) and cable platforms, effectively replacing [Ftn](/Ftn_(TV_channel)) on Freeview &#91;100&#93;.

In a significant strategic divestment, Virgin Media announced on 4 June 2010 that it had reached an agreement to sell Virgin Media Television to BSkyB. This transaction, of course, was subject to the usual regulatory approvals &#91;101&#93; &#91;102&#93;. For Sky, the acquisition was a clear win: it significantly expanded its portfolio of basic pay TV channels and, crucially, eliminated the carriage fees it had previously been obligated to pay for distributing VMtv channels on its own television services. As part of this complex deal, both companies also forged a number of new agreements concerning the carriage of specific Sky standard and high-definition (HD) channels. These included securing fresh carriage agreements for the wholesale distribution of Sky's core basic channel lineup, such as [Sky 1](/Sky_1) and [Sky Arts](/Sky_Arts), alongside the newly acquired VMtv channels, all to be carried on Virgin Media's cable TV service.

The Irish [Competition Authority](/Competition_Authority_(Ireland)) provided its clearance for the proposed transaction on 29 June 2010 &#91;103&#93;. Following this, BSkyB and Virgin Media jointly announced the completion of the acquisition on 13 July 2010 &#91;104&#93;. Post-acquisition, VMtv was rebranded and became known as the [Living TV Group](/Living_TV_Group). Sky's initial payment to Virgin Media for this acquisition amounted to £105 million, with a provision for an additional payment of up to £55 million upon securing UK regulatory clearance.

On 20 July 2010, the [Office of Fair Trading](/Office_of_Fair_Trading) (OFT) declared its intention to review BSkyB's acquisition of Virgin Media Television, specifically to assess whether the deal posed any potential competition concerns within the UK market &#91;105&#93;. However, by 14 September 2010, the OFT concluded its review, deciding not to refer BSkyB's takeover of Virgin Media's TV channels to the [Competition Commission](/Competition_Commission) &#91;106&#93;. Notably, [Virgin1](/Virgin1) was also part of this extensive deal, but it underwent a rebranding to Channel One on 3 September 2010 &#91;107&#93; &#91;108&#93;, as the "Virgin" name was, quite logically, not licensed for use by Sky. These new carriage agreements, a testament to the long-term strategic planning involved, were struck for an impressive duration of up to nine years &#91;109&#93;, a significant departure from the more common three-year deals that had typically been negotiated previously.

### Sit-up

*   Main article: [Bid Shopping](/Bid_Shopping)

Virgin Media, for a period, held ownership of Sit-up Ltd, a UK-based broadcaster specializing in home shopping television channels. This venture began as a joint partnership from its inception in 2000, with Virgin Media assuming full ownership in May 2005. Sit-up operated a suite of channels dedicated to direct sales, including [Bid TV](/Bid_(TV_channel)), [Price Drop TV](/Price_Drop), and [Speed Auction TV](/Bid_Plus). These channels were widely accessible across various platforms: digital satellite, cable, and terrestrial television, as well as via the internet. However, on 1 April 2009, Virgin Media confirmed its decision to divest this operation, announcing the sale of Sit-up to Aurelius AG for an unspecified sum &#91;110&#93;. A clear signal of the company's intent to streamline its focus away from niche content ownership.

### Virgin Media Pioneers

Virgin Media Pioneers functioned as an [online community](/Online_community) specifically designed to support British entrepreneurs, providing a platform for sharing tips, advice, and crucial networking opportunities. Launched in 2010, this initiative was a brainchild of Virgin Media, an attempt at fostering a more engaged ecosystem for new businesses. In 2011, Virgin Media Pioneers spearheaded the "Control Shift Campaign" &#91;111&#93;, a significant undertaking that surveyed over 1,600 aspiring young entrepreneurs. The campaign sought to gather their perspectives on potential governmental changes that could facilitate the creation of new businesses. The tangible outcome of this advocacy was the introduction of a £10 million Youth Enterprise Loan &#91;112&#93;, demonstrating a direct impact on policy.

### UKTV

*   Main article: [UKTV](/UKTV)

[UKTV](/UKTV) stands as a prominent digital cable and satellite television network, originally established as a joint venture between [BBC Worldwide](/BBC_Worldwide) – the commercial arm of the BBC – and Virgin Media. At its zenith, it was recognized as one of the United Kingdom's largest television companies &#91;113&#93;. However, on 15 August 2011, Virgin Media agreed to divest its 50% stake in UKTV, selling it to [Scripps Networks Interactive](/Scripps_Networks_Interactive) in a substantial deal valued at £339 million. Scripps' payment structure involved £239 million in cash, alongside approximately £100 million allocated to acquire the outstanding preferred stock and debt that UKTV owed to Virgin Media &#91;114&#93;. The completion of this intricate transaction was, as is standard, contingent upon receiving regulatory approvals from authorities in Ireland and Jersey, which were duly granted on 3 October 2011 &#91;115&#93;. This marked another step in Virgin Media's strategic shift away from content ownership.

## Corporate affairs

### Ownership

Following the successful completion of the complex merger between NTL and Telewest, and the subsequent acquisition of Virgin Mobile, the newly formed entity solidified its identity through a pivotal 30-year licensing agreement with [Sir Richard Branson](/Richard_Branson)'s [Virgin Group](/Virgin_Group). This agreement granted the company the right to utilize the globally recognized Virgin brand, a deal that notably included a ten-year opt-out clause. As part of this arrangement, Branson accepted a combination of shares and cash, which, at the time, positioned him as a significant 10.7% shareholder in the combined enterprise &#91;116&#93;.

In July 2007, demonstrating a shrewd financial strategy, Virgin Group hedged 37% of its stake in Virgin Media. This was achieved through a collared loan agreement with [Credit Suisse](/Credit_Suisse), valued at $224 million. This particular transaction allowed Virgin Group to retain both its voting and dividend rights while effectively mitigating some of the financial risk associated with its holdings. Virgin Group held an option to repurchase the 12.8 million Virgin Media shares that had been mortgaged after a two-year period, but in May 2009, the decision was made against exercising this option. The capital freed up from this financial maneuver was strategically redeployed by Virgin Group into other ventures across its diverse portfolio, including the launch of the [Virgin Green Fund](/Virgin_Green_Fund) in September 2007, as well as investments in [Virgin America](/Virgin_America) and [Virgin Mobile India](/Virgin_Mobile_India) &#91;117&#93;. By December 2009, Sir Richard Branson's Virgin Entertainment Investment Holdings Limited maintained a minority holding of 21,413,099 Virgin Media common stock &#91;118&#93;, which still rendered him the third-largest shareholder, a testament to his enduring influence.

However, the corporate landscape was again reshaped on 5 February 2013, when [Liberty Global](/Liberty_Global) announced its agreement to acquire Virgin Media. The deal, a substantial stock and cash merger, was valued at approximately US$23.3 billion (£15 billion) &#91;38&#93;. Following shareholder approval on 4 June &#91;40&#93;, the acquisition was formally completed on 7 June &#91;41&#93;. This transition saw Virgin Media become a wholly owned subsidiary of Liberty Global.

The most recent chapter in Virgin Media's ownership saga unfolded in 2020, with the announcement of a monumental merger with [O2](/O2_(UK)). This strategic union created a 50:50 joint venture, forming the behemoth known as [Virgin Media O2](/Virgin_Media_O2). The governance structure of this new entity was carefully designed, with an eight-person board of directors split equally between Liberty Global and Telefónica. The chairmanship of this formidable board is set to rotate between the two parent companies every few years &#91;119&#93;, a carefully balanced arrangement to manage shared control.

### Market share

[Ofcom’s](/Ofcom) 2024 Communications Market Report provided a clear snapshot of Virgin Media's standing in the fiercely competitive UK broadband sector, indicating that the company commanded a respectable 22% market share &#91;120&#93;. In the television market, the landscape proved more dynamic. While Virgin Media reported having 3.4 million TV subscribers in 2021, it was simultaneously acknowledged that the market was undergoing considerable disruption due to the surging popularity of [streaming services](/Streaming_media) &#91;121&#93;. A predictable shift, as consumers increasingly opt for flexible, on-demand content over traditional bundles.

### Advertising

Virgin Media's grand launch in February 2007 was heralded by a meticulously orchestrated public relations event and an undeniably expensive advertising campaign. This media blitz saturated major UK television channels, prominent newspapers, and ubiquitous billboards, ensuring maximum brand visibility. Over the years, its television advertisements have featured a diverse array of celebrity talent, including the actress [Uma Thurman](/Uma_Thurman) &#91;122&#93;, the comedian [Ruby Wax](/Ruby_Wax) &#91;123&#93;, and actors such as [Samuel L. Jackson](/Samuel_L._Jackson) &#91;124&#93;, [Marc Warren](/Marc_Warren), and [David Tennant](/David_Tennant) &#91;125&#93;.

Beyond traditional advertising, Virgin Media also engaged in high-profile sponsorships. Notably, it sponsored [Channel 4's](/Channel_4) immensely popular reality TV show, [Big Brother](/Big_Brother_(UK)), for its [eighth](/Big_Brother_8_(UK)) series in 2007, followed by its [Celebrity Hijack](/Big_Brother:_Celebrity_Hijack) and [ninth](/Big_Brother_9_(UK)) series in 2008 &#91;126&#93;.

In October 2010, the company launched another memorable campaign, this time featuring the iconic [Looney Tunes](/Looney_Tunes) character, [Speedy Gonzales](/Speedy_Gonzales). Speedy was not merely a fleeting guest; he served as a prominent mascot for the company, his image plastered across the UK, notably in [London Underground](/London_Underground) stations, and appearing in television adverts during commercial breaks for popular shows like [The X Factor](/The_X_Factor) on [ITV](/ITV1). His presence extended even further, appearing in-game and across various web platforms &#91;127&#93;.

A few years later, in 2012, Virgin Media rolled out a multi-million-pound advertising campaign to champion its superfast broadband service. This campaign starred the legendary sprinter [Usain Bolt](/Usain_Bolt) alongside Virgin founder Sir [Richard Branson](/Richard_Branson). The television adverts, directed by [Seth Gordon](/Seth_Gordon), notably featured Bolt playfully impersonating Branson &#91;128&#93;, a quirky touch designed to capture attention.

Demonstrating a commitment to sports marketing, on 8 June 2016, [Southampton F.C.](/Southampton_F.C.) announced that Virgin Media would become the club's principal shirt sponsor under a new three-year deal &#91;129&#93;. These varied and often high-profile campaigns underscore Virgin Media's consistent efforts to maintain brand visibility and attract new customers in a competitive market.

## Controversies

### Net neutrality

In April 2008, [Neil Berkett](/Neil_Berkett), then acting CEO of Virgin Media, ignited a significant controversy with a rather blunt statement. In an interview with *Television*, a magazine published by the [Royal Television Society](/Royal_Television_Society), Berkett dismissively declared that "this [net neutrality](/Net_neutrality) thing is a load of bollocks" &#91;130&#93;. According to the journalist, he further elaborated, suggesting that any video content provider unwilling to pay Virgin Media a premium for expedited access would find their content relegated to "bus lanes," experiencing significantly slower delivery speeds to end users compared to paying providers. This incendiary stance, which directly challenged the fundamental principle of equal access to internet traffic, predictably sparked widespread outrage across the internet. Calls for Virgin customers to terminate their subscriptions and initiate a mass boycott quickly proliferated &#91;131&#93;.

Virgin Media, facing intense public and industry backlash, swiftly moved into damage control, asserting that Berkett's comments had been taken out of context and misinterpreted &#91;132&#93;. A statement subsequently released by the company attempted to clarify its position: "With Virgin Media rolling out a 50 Mb service later this year, we are uniquely equipped to cope with the demand for new bandwidth-hungry services. We strongly support the principle that the internet should remain a space that is open to all and we have not called for content providers to pay for distribution. However, we recognise that as more customers turn to the web for content, different providers will have different needs and priorities and in the long term, it's legitimate to question how this demand will be managed. We welcome an informed debate on this issue." A predictable corporate pivot from provocative candor to cautious diplomacy, attempting to reframe a controversial statement as a call for "informed debate."

### Crackdown on illegal filesharing of copyrighted material

On 2 April 2008, [The Daily Telegraph](/The_Daily_Telegraph) published a report suggesting that Virgin Media was preparing to conduct a trial aimed at taking action against subscribers engaged in the illegal downloading of copyrighted material via internet [Peer-to-peer (P2P)](/Peer-to_peer) services &#91;133&#93; &#91;134&#93;. The report detailed a process whereby data on alleged offenders would be supplied by the [British Phonographic Industry](/British_Phonographic_Industry) (BPI), after which Virgin Media and the BPI would jointly dispatch a warning letter to the customer. However, both Virgin Media and the BPI promptly denied the specifics of these reports, stating they were merely engaged in ongoing discussions on the matter &#91;135&#93;. Despite these denials, at least one individual publicly claimed to have received a letter explicitly threatening disconnection of their service &#91;136&#93;. This period coincided with attempts by the UK government to implement measures that could effectively ban P2P users from the internet, a policy that faced strong condemnation from the European Parliament on grounds of privacy concerns and the fundamental importance of internet access &#91;137&#93;. In July 2008, the BBC reported that approximately 800 Virgin Media customers had indeed received letters, conspicuously delivered in envelopes emblazoned with the stark warning: "If you don't read this, your broadband connection could be disconnected." At least one recipient of such a letter vehemently denied any wrongdoing &#91;138&#93;.

The saga continued on 26 November 2009, with revelations that Virgin Media was planning a trial of [deep packet inspection](/Deep_packet_inspection) (DPI) technology. The stated purpose was to measure the extent of illegal file sharing occurring on its network &#91;139&#93;. This move, which raised significant privacy concerns, caught the attention of international bodies. On 22 January 2010, the [European Commission](/European_Commission) confirmed that, while it had not directly discussed the matter with Virgin Media, it would "closely monitor" the trial &#91;140&#93;. [Privacy International](/Privacy_International), a prominent advocacy group, announced its intention to file a criminal report with the [Metropolitan Police](/Metropolitan_Police), arguing that the trial would constitute a breach of laws requiring explicit informed consent or a judicial warrant for such surveillance.

Ultimately, the company resorted to more direct measures. On 3 May 2012, reports confirmed that Virgin Media had become the first [ISP](/Internet_service_provider) in the UK to implement a [web filter](/Content-control_software) designed to block access to the infamous torrent site [The Pirate Bay](/The_Pirate_Bay). This action was taken in compliance with a UK High Court order issued in April &#91;141&#93;. Of course, as is often the case with such blocking efforts, users quickly found workarounds through various mirrors, proxies, or [VPNs](/Virtual_private_network) &#91;142&#93;, highlighting the inherent futility of attempting to fully control internet access.

### Billing dead customers

In a rather unfortunate display of corporate insensitivity and procedural oversight, Virgin Media garnered significant criticism in 2009 when it came to light that the company was cutting off services to the relatives of deceased customers due to non-payment of bills. This deeply distressing practice was brought to widespread public attention through a segment on [BBC](/BBC)'s consumer affairs program, [Watchdog](/Watchdog_(TV_programme)). The incident even inspired musician [Mitch Benn](/Mitch_Benn) to compose a satirical song titled "Virgin Bills Dead People" &#91;143&#93;, solidifying the issue in the public consciousness. A disturbingly similar incident resurfaced in 2013, where a bill sent to a deceased account holder inexplicably included an automated bank message explicitly stating that the account holder was deceased &#91;144&#93;. These incidents underscored a profound lack of empathy and a clear failure in their customer service protocols, proving that sometimes, even basic human decency escapes the automated systems.

### Charging exit fees

Virgin Media previously imposed exit fees on customers who relocated to areas where the company's services were unavailable. This practice, while common, often led to customer dissatisfaction. From 2017 to 2018, [Ofcom](/Ofcom), the UK's communications regulator, launched an investigation into Virgin Media's early termination charges. The investigation concluded that Virgin Media had, between 2016 and 2017, contravened Ofcom's General Conditions. Specifically, it failed to publish clear and up-to-date information regarding these charges and, worse, set them at rates higher than contractually agreed upon. As a consequence, Virgin Media was fined £7 million &#91;145&#93;.

As part of the resolution, Virgin Media committed to making it explicitly clear to customers that early termination charges might apply if they moved outside the company's network coverage area. Furthermore, it agreed to allow customers who moved within the network area to continue on their existing contracts, rather than forcing them into new fixed terms, a small but significant concession. In a more definitive move, Virgin Media announced in 2022 that it would completely cease the practice of charging customers an exit fee when they moved to a home where its services were not available &#91;146&#93; &#91;147&#93;. A welcome change, albeit one that required regulatory intervention and a hefty fine to enact.

### Data pimping

In early 2008, a rather unsavory revelation emerged concerning the [ISP](/Internet_service_provider) arm of Virgin Media. It was announced that the company had entered into a contract—alongside industry peers BT and TalkTalk—with [Phorm](/Phorm), a company with a rather dubious past, having previously operated as a [spyware](/Spyware) firm (under its 121Media guise, it was responsible for the Apropos [rootkit](/Rootkit)) &#91;148&#93; &#91;149&#93;. The purpose of this contract was to intercept and meticulously analyze users' click-stream data, subsequently selling this anonymized aggregate information as part of Phorm's OIX advertising service &#91;150&#93; &#91;151&#93;. This practice, quickly and accurately dubbed "data pimping," triggered an immediate and intense outcry from various internet communities and concerned parties. Many vehemently argued that the interception of such data was unequivocally illegal under UK law, specifically the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act (RIPA) &#91;152&#93; &#91;153&#93;.

Initially, Phorm, ever the optimist, claimed that Virgin Media had signed an exclusive contract and was fully committed to implementing Phorm's "Webwise" tracking system. However, under mounting public pressure and scrutiny, Virgin Media subsequently began to distance itself from the controversial partnership. The company clarified its position, stating that it had only signed a preliminary contract with Phorm, intended solely for the purpose of better understanding the tracking technology, and that it was under no obligation whatsoever to actually implement it &#91;154&#93;. Reports published on The Guardian website in May 2008 further corroborated Virgin Media's efforts to disassociate itself from the contentious system &#91;155&#93;. A classic corporate retreat, demonstrating the power of public outrage against perceived privacy invasions.

### Wikipedia censorship

In a rather peculiar incident that highlighted the complexities of content filtering, in December 2008, Virgin Media found itself among several UK [ISPs](/Internet_service_provider) that attempted to restrict its users' access to a specific [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) article. The article in question detailed the 1976 album [Virgin Killer](/Virgin_Killer) by the stadium rock band [Scorpions](/Scorpions_(band)) &#91;156&#93;. The album cover, which controversially featured a partially obscured image of a naked, underage girl, had been flagged. The article itself was blacklisted by the [Internet Watch Foundation](/Internet_Watch_Foundation) (IWF) following a user complaint. However, the blacklisting was ultimately, and sensibly, rescinded, demonstrating that even well-intentioned censorship can sometimes overreach, especially when targeting informational resources rather than illegal content itself.

### 10-month exposure to data theft

In March 2020, a significant lapse in data security came to light, revealing that a Virgin Media marketing database, containing the personal details (including phone numbers, home addresses, and email addresses) of a staggering 900,000 users, had been left unsecured for a period of 10 months. The company, in an admission of fault, acknowledged that a member of their staff had failed to adhere to correct security procedures, directly resulting in the system's vulnerability. It was confirmed that at least one instance of unauthorized access to this exposed data had occurred. Following the resolution of the vulnerability, a comprehensive forensic investigation was launched to ascertain the full extent and impact of this substantial data breach &#91;157&#93;. A costly reminder that human error, even in an age of advanced cybersecurity, remains a persistent and dangerous vulnerability.

### Failure to protect vulnerable customers

In a deeply concerning incident that underscored systemic failings, Virgin Media was fined a substantial £23.8 million by [Ofcom](/Ofcom), the UK's communications regulator, in December 2025. As of that date, this punitive measure marked the third-largest fine ever imposed on a communications provider by Ofcom.

The core of the issue stemmed from Virgin Media's transition of customers from their legacy analogue to modern digital telephone service during November and December 2023. This industry-wide shift was necessitated by the aging copper line infrastructure, which is increasingly classified as outdated technology.

